node.text:
Some of my go-tos! Enjoy 😊 

Greek Inspired Salad Jar
* 1-2 cups kale
* 1 tbsp feta cheese
* 4oz chicken thighs 
* 10 olives 
* ¼ cup red onion 
* ½ orange bell pepper 
* ½ cup chickpeas
* 1 tbsp balsamic

BLT Remix Salad jar 
* 1 cup mixed greens
* 2 pieces nitrate free bacon
* 2 eggs 
* ½ cup cucumber 
* 1 cup tomatoes 
* 2 tbsp paleo ranch

Veggie Goddess
* 1 cup mixed greens
* ½ cup red onion 
* ½ cup black beans 
* ½ cup quinoa
* ½ cup cucumber 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Tex Mex Jar Combo 
* 1 tbsp cilantro 
* 2 cup lettuce   
* 4oz ground turkey or grass-fed ground beef
* ½ cup corn
* ¼ cup onion 
* ½ cup bell peppers 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Coconut oil pulling benefits:
Fights bad breath,
improves gum health &
maintains teeth whitness.

What to do:
Step 1: Swish 1 tbsp coconut oil in your mouth for 10-15 min (yes min!) Step 2: Spit in trash afterwards since oil will clog the drains
Step 3: Brush your teeth normally after and floss like you normally would.

Cheers to great oral health!
Xoxo
Amanda

node.text:
Make time for you ❤️ Because you deserve to feel your best.⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
The default state of any organism is health. And it doesn’t come from some fringe diet. It doesn’t come from a cross-fit regimen. It doesn’t come from a supplement. And it doesn’t come counting calories. These are all tools and should be used as such but the primary variable is you. What are you doing every day to create habits that will lead you to your best, most optimal self? It doesn’t have to be all or nothing—as long as you’re progressing daily (and this could be in terms of your diet, the scale, your lifts, your sleep quality, or even your mindset) you’re on the right path.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁠⁠
Also, this shouldn’t be taken to imply that by doing everything “right” (i.e. some illusory notion of perfection) that illness is completely avoidable. Definitely not so. Genes and, to be honest, luck also play a part and for that we have modern medicine. But when it comes to lifestyle conditions, by far the most common ailments affecting humans today, the research is clear: we do have a say.⁣⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
Caption by my friend @MaxLugavere⁠⁠
Image by Unknown (DM me or comment for credit)⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
I share this post with you out of the love and compassion of my heart. Making yourself a priority too is not selfish, it’s necessary.⁠⁠
xx,⁠⁠
Amanda⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
What’s your drink of choice? ☕️ 🍵 ⁠
⁠
Whether you’re a matcha lover or coffee addict, it’s great to get a gauge of where your caffeine level is landing. While there’s no guide to where you should exactly land, if you notice yourself feeling extra jittery, anxious or cracked out, that may be a sign you’re overdoing it in the caffeine arena. The amount can also vary wildly per brand so make sure to check in with yourself & how you’re feeling. ⁠
⁠
For people more sensitive to caffeine, matcha and green tea can often be a great choice not just because of the often lower caffeine levels but the L-Theanine found in these drinks that can help to balance out the jittery feeling often associated with caffeine while still helping to improve focus & energy. ⁠
⁠
Lastly, herbal teas are a great way to enjoy a delightlful drink without adding extra caffeine to your day.⁠
⁠
Reminder that caffeine levels will vary by amount and brand so double check with your local coffee shop or brand sourced if you’re looking for the exact amount of caffeine in your drink.⁠
⁠
*Average amounts listed for: 12oz nitro, 12oz cold brew, 12oz coffee, 1 espresso shot, 1 teaspoon of matcha mixed w/ 12oz hot water, 1 bag black tea, 1 bag green tea, 1 bag herbal tea*⁠
⁠
Inspired by @collegenutritionist⁠
⁠

node.text:
Sugar is hidden in more foods than many are aware of!⁠
⁠
That’s why it’s more important now than ever to become an informed consumer. It’s up to you to take matters of your health into your own hands.⁠
⁠
The book @sugarproofkids by Michael L. Goran, PhD is a great deep dive into all things sugar and what you can do about it.⁠
⁠
One key takeaway is that while a lot of sugars are similar, fructose is a the type of sugar you’ll want to minimize overall when it’s not paired with the appropriate fiber.⁠
⁠
Fructose found in fruit is encapsulated in a fiber-rich flesh which helps to slow the absorption down, making it a lighter load on your liver.⁠
⁠
High fructose corn syrup, agave nectar and fruit juice concentrates are all examples of sweeteners with a higher concentration of fructose that you’d want to minimize overall.⁠
⁠
Remember that the most important thing is paying attention to your total sugar load for the day and when you can opt for whole fruit over added sugars 😘⁠
⁠

Back to school 📕- COLLEGE AGE⁠⁠
⁠⁠
While everyone is headed back to school we can’t forget about our college students!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Love this post by @just.ingredients , she shares great swaps! More below:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Not surprisingly, their immune systems can take a hit, due to some college kids lifestyles. So here are some tips to help keep college age kids healthy this year!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
1️⃣Sleep-⁠⁠
It’s often not a priority-those late nights and early classes can take a toll!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
During sleep, the brain not only consolidates learning and memory but also strengthens immune memory. Sleep “reinforces the immune systems ability to remember how to recognize and react to dangerous antigens. Getting enough high quality sleep facilitates the delicate balance of immune function.”1⁠⁠
⁠⁠
2️⃣Nutrition-⁠⁠
Nourishing food often takes a back seat and Top Ramen and soda are considered a meal😬⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Meals that consist primarily of processed foods and little to no nutrition can negatively affect a healthy immune system. This kind of diet can “promote disturbances in healthy intestinal microorganisms, resulting in suppressed immunity.” 2⁠⁠
⁠⁠
👉🏻College students are often on a budget and may think that some of the better options aren’t possible. Walmart has a great affordable organic line, as seen above.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And there are some easy changes they can make that are little to no cost:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
🍎add a fruit or vegetable to each meal⁠⁠
🥦buy frozen vegetables. These are a great choice because they’re picked at peak ripeness and are generally less expensive⁠⁠
🥚have an egg for a quick, protein filled snack⁠⁠
🌾have organic oats on hand for a quick meal⁠⁠
🥣pick a yogurt with live probiotics⁠⁠
❌buy foods without artificial sweeteners⁠⁠
✅use glass food storage containers⁠⁠

🧽an all purpose cleaner can be used for cleaning most things⁠⁠
🧺use wool dryer balls⁠⁠
🧴use Castile soap for hand soap⁠⁠
🪴add a plant or two for better air quality⁠⁠
⛅️open the windows for fresh air⁠⁠
💦drink plenty of filtered water⁠⁠
☀️get some vitamin D through sunshine⁠⁠
🏃‍♀️move your body regularly ⁠⁠
😴get 7-8 hours of sleep⁠⁠
🌱use adaptogens like ashwagandha if stressed

Tips on How to Fix Bloating + Tips To Support A Healthy Gut⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Causes of bloating can be complex and not fun for those who experience it frequently. I wanted to share some tips with you on what could be triggering bloating and ways to fix it. Now, this isn’t a one-size-fits all approach. These are some tips that have helped me and I hope they can help you too.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Additionally, the gut is one of the most important organs in your body that directly affects how you feel, & many other aspects of overall health. That’s why it’s crucial to support a healthy gut with proper nutrition & a healthy lifestyle.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 1: Eat mindfully and slowly - Ensuring adequate chewing of your food can have two benefits - reducing the amount of air you swallow (which can cause bloating) & eating slower gives your body more time to signal feelings of fullness.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 2: Limit sugar alcohols - sugar alcohols in high amounts can also lead to bloating.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 3: Watch your fiber intake - Eating too much or too little fiber can also cause bloating, so find a happy medium!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 4: Mix in fermented foods or a probiotic - probiotics found in fermented foods or a supplement can help improve the bacterial environment in the gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 5: Drink lemon ginger or peppermint tea - Both ginger & peppermint have been shown to sooth & aid w/ digestion.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 6: Check for underlying food sensitives/allergies.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 7:  Drink lots of water: Proper hydration has been shown to have a beneficial effect on the balance of good bacteria in the gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 8: Prioritize sleep: Quality of sleep can have serious impacts on your gut health.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 9: Limit processed Foods: A diet high in ultra processed foods and added sugars can cause an imbalance of good bacteria in your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 10: Eat prebiotic: fibers are foods that promote the growth of beneficial microbes in your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 11: Manage street levels: Chronic high levels of stress can have an array of negative affects including a negative impact on your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠

How to Build a Delicious Homemade Salad Dressing (Swipe to see some salad ideas to go with each dressing)⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠There are so many ways to get creative with building a healthy salad dressing at home! That’s why I thought I’d share some inspiration using common base ingredients, vinegars/citrus, herbs & more in case you’re looking for some inspiration! ⁠⁠
While there are definitely some healthier pre-made salad dressings out there, a lot of store-bought salad dressings contain unhealthy oils, additives, sugars, etc., making it a good choice to make your own at home when possible. Not only are homemade dressings delicious and easy to make, but they can be customized to your liking and saved for later so you don’t have to make a new batch for every meal.⁠⁠
Details on each dressing below:⁠⁠
What you need for each dressing (note: don’t forget to add desired seasoning like salt, pepper, garlic, etc)⁠⁠
What you need for the Yogurt Ranch:⁠⁠
(makes 1 cup)⁠⁠
-½ cup Greek yogurt⁠⁠
-1 tbsp ACV ⁠⁠
-1.5 tbsp chives, chopped ⁠⁠
-1 tsp honey  ⁠⁠
What you need for the Balsamic Vinaigrette:⁠⁠
(makes about 1 cup)⁠⁠
- 1 cup olive oil ⁠⁠
-¼ cup balsamic ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp basil, minced ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp dijon mustard⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Creamy Tomato:⁠⁠
(makes ¾ cup) ⁠⁠
-½ cup paleo mayo⁠⁠
-1 tbsp white wine vinegar ⁠⁠
-1 tsp parsley, minced ⁠⁠
-½ cup sun dried tomatoes ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Lemon Ginger Tahini:⁠⁠
(makes ½-¾ cup)⁠⁠
-½ cup tahini ⁠⁠
-2 tbsp lemon juice ⁠⁠
-1 tsp ginger, minced ⁠⁠
-2 tsp maple syrup⁠⁠
What to do:⁠⁠
1- If making the Creamy Tomato, combine all ingredients in a blender and blend until smooth (you may need to add 1-2 tbsps water to help with blending).⁠⁠
2- For the others, mix together all ingredients in a large bowl until well combined. ⁠⁠
3- Enjoy right away or save for later. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Which would you choose?⁠⁠

Therapy changed my life ❤️⁠
⁠
It really did. First time therapy saved my life was when I had an eating disorder in high school. I remember my mom super being stressed out about how thin I was getting. I was definitely in full-denial at first.⁠
⁠
It wasn’t until my doctor said I would need professional help because I was at a dangerously low weight that things started to turn around. I was 97 pounds at my lowest (over 36 lbs lighter than I am now) and I remember contemplating putting dumbbells in my sweat shirt pockets so the doctor wouldn’t know my real weight. ⁠
⁠
That was my first introduction to therapy and I can’t be more thankful for it. Having the accountability and emotional support I needed to work through my eating disorder was priceless.⁠
⁠
Again in my late 20s. I knew something was up with the way I handled conflict in interpersonal relationships but I didn’t know just what to do about it.⁠
⁠
I was so timid to be honest in my relationships about how I truly felt. I was so lost in pleasing other people that I actually lost part of myself in the process. Out of touch with my own emotions and being pushed around by others wasn’t getting me the deep, meaningful relationships I craved.⁠
⁠
I also knew the way I handled conflict in avoidance or passive aggressive manner wasn’t going to lead to a positive place and I wanted to change that.⁠
⁠
Working through some of my conflict-avoidance, passive-aggressive & people-pleasing tendencies was much more difficult than I thought it would be but it was well worth it!⁠
⁠
So if there’s anything I want you to take away is that you can most definitely make impactful change in your life. Sometimes it’s just about asking for the right help 😘⁠
⁠
I’m still a work-in-process but I’m so thankful you’re here for the wild ride with me!⁠
⁠
Amanda⁠
⁠
#mentalhealth #therapy

Swipe for different gut-healing foods (and save this post!) 👉🏼⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁠⁠
When it comes to eating for gut health, there are different strategies to take, and there's no one-size-fits-all recommendation! You have to figure out what works for you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Great post by my friend @maxlugavere ⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
More in this post below:⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Soluble fiber absorbs water and forms a gel, and feeds the bacteria that live in your large intestine, collectively known as your gut microbiome. As a result, those bacteria churn out powerful metabolites including short-chain fatty acids like butyrate. This type of fiber may help improve symptoms in people with IBS.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Insoluble fiber doesn't absorb water, but instead acts as an abrasive broom, sweeping up your GI tract. This type of fiber is usually well tolerated but can cause or exacerbate symptoms for some sensitive people, including people with IBS.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Resistant starch is a form of carbohydrate that acts like a fiber, is resistant to digestion and instead feeds those microbes at the latter end of your GI tract. There are multiple types of resistant starch. One form is found in unripe bananas/mangos, and another can be created when you cook and cool a starch, like a potato or rice. This is why sushi rice is actually quite healthy—b/c it's cooked and cooled.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Probiotic foods contain live and active bacteria cultures. These are some of my favorites! These are pretty well tolerated except by people with histamine issues.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Love you guys!⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
🥰 Amanda⁠⁠

The difference between sugar with some coffee, and coffee with some flavor! (Swipe to see some healthier coffee options) ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Now there’s nothing wrong with treating yourself to these drinks on occasion, but consuming them regularly can really add up.⁠⁠ ⁠⁠

It’s important to be aware of how much sugar you’re consuming each day. While it’s totally okay to have some days with a higher sugar intake than others, your overall consumption plays a crucial role in your health. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Added sugars like those in most Starbucks coffee drinks can become highly addicting, leading your body to crave more. That’s why I recommend going for coffee with some flavor like honey, stevia, cacao, etc. on a more regular basis. Plus, they’re straight up delicious! ⁠⁠
